data.name: Label135.Text
data.value: Standardized profile assumes soil profile data is raw data. It ignores the delta values and automatically conforms the data to the discretization scheme selected here. Additionally, the profile will be extended to the depth selected here and the water contents below 10 cm will be adjusted to reflect halfway between field cap and porosity. The last line will be saturated and assumed to be the aquifer output of interest. The lowest profile characteristics will be extrapolated to all points below. This conforms to the NAFTA standard GW profile, ensuring proper dispersion.

data.name: Label132.Text
data.value: Vertical Dispersion is controlled by numerical dispersion through the backward differencing of the finite difference routine implemented in the transport calculations. Larger increments mean larger amounts of dispersion. Dispersion can be precisely controlled by specifying the appropriate increments in the adjacent table. USEPA recommends the values in the adjacent table. This example depicts an aquifer surface 300 cm below soil surface and well screen of 1 meter (lastline). Aquifer screen (where output is taken) is from the compartments of the last line. Depth should only be adjusted by changing the 5th row and the 50 cm increment size should be maintained.

data.name: Label101.Text
data.value: A scheme is a pesticide application method and the crops and regions it applies to. Schemes are managed on this tab. To create or modify a scheme, check the Edit box, and then populate the Applications and Scenarios tabs. After you have created or modified a scheme, you must push the Commit button to register the changes.
